{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608558"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:32:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:32:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16007"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16007"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.04,0.15,0.33,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8698"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73465"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8698"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16007"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58934"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"6739"},{"type":"tags","id":"8576"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20810"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20812"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73465"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring early embryonic development, the face forms through complex tissue movements and interactions. The nose and nasal passages develop from specific embryological structures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the embryological origin of the nasal pit?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A pharyngeal arch derivative forming the external nose","A neural crest cell population forming the nasal bones","An endodermal pouch forming the paranasal sinuses","An ectodermal invagination forming the primitive nasal cavity","A mesodermal outgrowth forming the nasal septum"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eectodermal invagination forming the primitive nasal cavity\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes the nasal pit. This structure develops during the fourth week of embryonic development when surface ectoderm invaginates to create the primitive nasal cavity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA pharyngeal arch derivative forming the external nose\u003C/strong\u003E - The external nose develops from the frontonasal prominence, not directly from pharyngeal arches\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA neural crest cell population forming the nasal bones\u003C/strong\u003E - While nasal bones do develop from neural crest cells, this is not the nasal pit\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAn endodermal pouch forming the paranasal sinuses\u003C/strong\u003E - Paranasal sinuses develop later as outgrowths of the nasal cavity, not from endodermal pouches\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA mesodermal outgrowth forming the nasal septum\u003C/strong\u003E - The nasal septum develops from neural crest cells, not mesoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe nasal pits continue to deepen and eventually break through to form the primitive choana, establishing a connection between the nasal and oral cavities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The nasal pit is an ectodermal invagination that forms the primitive nasal cavity during early embryonic development.","Nasal pit formation occurs during week 4 of embryonic development as part of facial development.","The nasal pit eventually breaks through to form the primitive choana, connecting nasal and oral cavities."],"references":["Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Som PM, Naidich TP. Illustrated review of the embryology and development of the facial region, part 1: Early face and lateral nasal cavities. AJNR Am J Neuroradiol. 2013 Dec;34(12):2233-40. doi: 10.3174/ajnr.A3415. Epub 2013 Mar 14. PMID: 23493891; PMCID: PMC7965203."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58934"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16007"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58934"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T21:21:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T21:23:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8698"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73465"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attrib